data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement — `Thread.Abort()` forcibly kills a thread that exceeds a time limit.

**APIs to replace:**
| API | Line | Replacement |
|-----|------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | timeout branch | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | worker lambda | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | worker lambda | Remove entirely |

**Key paradigm shift:** `Thread.Abort()` forcibly injected an exception — the work didn't need to cooperate. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. You must switch to cooperative cancellation, meaning the work function must voluntarily check for cancellation.

---

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work function MUST check the CancellationToken for timeout to
    /// actually stop the work. Without checks, the task will be abandoned
    /// but the work continues running in the background until it completes.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner call stacks
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — pass the token through and check it
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        foreach (var item in items)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // checkpoint
            Process(item);
        }
        return ComputeResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work ignores the token** | If `work` never checks `ct`, the task runs to completion even after timeout. Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cooperative cancellation cannot interrupt code that doesn't cooperate. |
| **Blocking calls won't interrupt** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read`, etc. don't check tokens. Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` and use async I/O overloads that accept a `CancellationToken`. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. The timer inside `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` leaks if not disposed. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (here, to convert to `TimeoutException`). Don't catch and suppress it deeper in the call chain. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If you cannot modify `work` to accept a token (e.g., third-party library), there is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`. Move the work to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. |

### If you cannot modify callers (backward-compatible overload)

```csharp
// Keep the old signature as a convenience wrapper, but the work
// will NOT be cancellable — it runs until completion even on timeout.
[Obsolete("Use the overload accepting Func<CancellationToken, T> " +
          "for actual timeout enforcement.")]
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    return ExecuteWithTimeout(_ => work(), timeout);
}
```

This compiles, but the timeout only abandons the wait — it does **not** stop the work. Mark it `[Obsolete]` to push callers toward the cooperative version.
